Structure of state: design #1
(inappropriate with React Router though)

[
    {title: 'hello', id: 5, category: 'greetings', content: 'nice to see you'},
    {title: 'nice dog', id: 23, category: 'fun stuff', content: 'so cute'},
    ......
]
{title: 'nice dog', id: 23, category: 'fun stuff', content: 'so cute'}

However, with React Router, this is redundant because the
route URL say '/api/posts/23' already has the information. 

In other words, the route URL could be considered as another 
form of the state of our application.

Conclusion: The "active" object can be removed from the state.

Structure of state: design #2 
(appropriate with React Router)

{
    5: {title: 'hello', id: 5, category: 'greetings', content: 'nice to see you'},
    23: {title: 'nice dog', id: 23, category: 'fun stuff', content: 'so cute'},
    ......
}

If we store "posts" in an array, each post has not only an id (assigned by the backend API server) but also an array index. Most of the times, they are different values. So it's not an ideal and efficient structure when looking up a post through its id.

Conclusion: Change the structure of "posts" from an array of objects to a containing object of objects. Each object has a key which is the id of post itself.

Since posts are contained in an object, we can no longer manipulate them using helpers such as Array.map, Array.reduce, ... etc. However, we can use lodash, which provides a set of similar helper functions to deal with list of objects inside a containing object while observing the immutability rules.
